---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
	title="Sustainability"
	description="Sustainability on Irish golf courses: resource-efficient machinery, water management, and course resilience - practical measures, not slogans."
>
	<section class="section section--tight hero">
		<div class="container">
			<span class="eyebrow">Sustainability</span>
			<h1>Sustainability that shows up on the P&amp;L</h1>
			<p class="lede">
				On a working golf course, sustainability isn't a separate initiative, it's fuel, labour,
				water, and inputs used more deliberately. The measures below are chosen because they pay
				for themselves in reduced costs and extended playing days, not because they look good in
				a report.
			</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="section">
		<div class="container">
			<div class="grid grid--2">
				<div class="card">
					<h3>Water &amp; drainage</h3>
					<p>
						Getting rainfall off the course quickly is the single biggest lever on an Irish
						course's playing season. It also reduces compaction, disease pressure, and the inputs
						needed to recover surfaces after a wet spell.
					</p>
					<a href="/drainage/">See the Drainage programme →</a>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<h3>Robotic &amp; electric mowing</h3>
					<p>
						Autonomous and electric mowers cut fuel and labour costs, run quietly enough for early
						or late operation, and reduce soil compaction from repeated diesel machinery passes.
						The business case is covered in detail in our Technical Notes.
					</p>
					<a href="/technical-notes/">Read the Technical Notes →</a>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<h3>Surveying &amp; course mapping</h3>
					<p>
						Accurate drainage and course maps mean interventions are targeted rather than
						speculative, less material, less machinery time, and a permanent record for future
						work.
					</p>
					<a href="/services/surveys-maps/">See Surveys &amp; Maps →</a>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<h3>Climate resilience</h3>
					<p>
						Wetter winters and more intense rainfall events are already the operating reality for
						Irish courses. Resilience means engineering drainage and course structures for the
						climate we now have, not the one the course was originally built for.
					</p>
					<a href="/contact/">Talk through your course →</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="section section--alt">
		<div class="container" style="display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:1.5rem; align-items:center; justify-content:space-between;">
			<div>
				<h2 style="margin-top:0;">Where to start</h2>
				<p style="margin-bottom:0; max-width:34rem;">
					Most courses get the biggest early win from drainage, it's the fastest way to extend
					the playing season and reduce downstream costs. A free consultation identifies the
					priority order for your course.
				</p>
			</div>
			<a class="btn btn--primary" href="/contact/">Book a consultation</a>
		</div>
	</section>
</BaseLayout>
